\begin_layout Title
Status consumption under severe inequality 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

- a case study in Tanzania
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
Status consumption is known to be ubiquitous but the role of wealth inequalities
 and spatial exclusion status consumption is less understood in the varied
 contexts of developing countries.
 We develop a model for status consumption based on permanent ownership
 and high quality in non-durable consumption and use the durable goods ownership
 data available in the Tanzanian LSMS consumption microdata to discuss how
 a segregation of overall quality under conditions of price heterogeneity
 may characterise status consumption in a developing economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent research on conspicuous consumption suggests its prevalence in both
 the developed and developing economies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019,KausSA,ZahraIndia,JaikumarConspConIneq,FrieheGermany,heffetz_visibility"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The ubiquity of conspicuous consumption could imply that consumers maintain
 a consumption level relative to their reference group level regardless
 of how poor an economy is.
 However since reference groups themselves are subject to spatial and economic
 boundaries, the conspicuous consumption in an economy would depend on the
 extent to which the social reference groups are segmented across the population.
 It is quite possible thus that the demand for certain conspicuous goods
 (not commodities) is completely absent in some reference groups that are
 excluded spatially or economically 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The terminology of goods vs commodities provided by Cramer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CramerIncomePrice1973"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is used throughout the current chapter.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relevance of reference groups therefore provides a necessary qualification
 to the idea of pecuniary emulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in conspicuous consumption - as the consumers need not emulate the rich
 if their social reference is insulated from the higher requirements of
 income corresponding to a group outside their own social reference.
 If status competitions for a group do not include a significant number
 of consumers outside their own reference or peer group, the status consumption
 would be necessarily segmented across the groups formed on the basis of
 a particular social reference.
 One can hardly claim therefore that the poor majority in a largely impoverished
 economy observes and emulates the lifestyles of a rich microscopic minority.
 The opposing effects of poverty levels and peer-influences on status consumptio
n have not been explored in much detail in the literature - with the exception
 of some studies on the effects of income inequality on conspicuous consumption
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq,Duesenberry1949,ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Friehe et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrieheGermany"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 who observe visible consumption in the regions of erstwhile East and West
 Germany after the economic liberalisation at the end of cold war to test
 if prolonged measures of suppressed incomes can influence visible consumption
 when the incomes rise with economic changes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To explore status consumption in the context of wealth differences and social
 segmentation, we fall back to the notion of how status consumption is used
 to offset existing inequalities in income and economic standing.
 Instead of focusing on the disproportionate demand for signaling-goods
 (i.e.
 conspicuous consumption), therefore we adopt a model based on a social-deferenc
e view of status that has been embraced in many economic studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy,corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Our model considers permanent ownership ( owned long-term goods ) and quality
 consumption as the key indicators of status that offset the existing income
 and social hierarchies.
 If the role of status consumption is to influence a ranking of income and/or
 wealth, it follows that two consumers with the same personal characteristics
 and the same set of needs can compete with each other for status only with
 either quality in non-durable consumption or ownership of long-term durable
 goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effects of poverty and peer effects are incorporated in the model where
 a consumer uses obtains utility through her social characteristics, quality
 in non-durable consumption and long-term durable goods.
 The consumption for quality and permanent ownership subject to the heterogenous
 prices are then explored across different age-groups, regions and levels
 of urbanisation in an economy.
 The model endogenises the role that personal characteristics (such as social
 class, level of education) play in status through the ownership of long-term
 durable goods and the constraints on quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While measuring permanent ownership is relatively easy in the empirical
 analyses when the assets owned by consumers are recorded in the consumption
 microdata, the measurements of quality using conventional methods from
 demand literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,NelsonQualityQuantity,McKelveyQuality2011,McKenzie2005,GibsonKimQualityBog2019,DongShonkwierCappsQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 turn out to be less attractive due to their reliance on observed market
 prices of items.
 A workaround is implicitly adopted by the visible consumption studies -
 which focus on items that are assumed to be futile for common use (an assumptio
n attributed to Veblen
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Without the assumption of futility of conspicuous items, the sense of quality
 derived from an aggregation of items over commodities as separable groups
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,NelsonQualityQuantity,McKelveyQuality2011,McKenzie2005,GibsonKimQualityBog2019,DongShonkwierCappsQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 would depend on the observed prices of items.
 Thus while the futility assumption does ensure the separability of demand
 for visible goods, it does so at the cost of limiting oneself to a narrowed
 context of quality.
 With a more general notion of quality that permits any high-price non-durable
 consumption or a durable good to contribute to status - a notion which
 we feel is necessary to represent the conditions of a developing economy
 where basic needs are unmet for a significant part of society - we avoid
 making the futility assumption and rely on a view of quality as 
\shape italic
excess
\shape default
 non-durable consumption given the cost of basic needs (both external and
 internal) at a district-level granularity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the empirical analysis, therefore we use the context of the saving vs
 consumption problem under an observed heterogeneity of prices of permanent
 ownership and relative quality to understand the data from Living Standards
 Measurement Study (LSMS
