\end_inset

 and possession of long-term durable goods 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (see discussion in the Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:LiteratureReview"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 For example, the role of unavailability of certain goods in a particular
 region (e.g.
 electricity - particularly relevant in the context of developing countries)
 would be represented simply with a suppressed costs function 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reason why such constraints on choices are not entirely unrelated to
 the temporal hierarchy we have specified is that a certain commitment is
 always implied once a long-term choice is made.
 Certain costs are necessarily associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 - both of which (along with 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 if a consumer could change her characteristics) are long-term commitments
 of the consumer.
 If a consumer chooses to be on a trajectory of higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

, the consumer might have less concerns for status ( a choice where life-cycle
 effects have a direct influence).
 Similarly, the ownership of durable goods 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 also presents a commitment - albeit less inescapable than 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 - since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be sold in the market or rented out for income.
 The constraints which choices present are thus part of the temporal hierarchy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moving further into the dynamics of the model, we assume that at the end
 of the lifetime of a consumer, the personal wealth of the consumer would
 either be consumed or would be passed on to her progeny so that the asset
 account at the end of the lifetime becomes starting wealth of some other
 household(s) in the economy.
 Consequently, all consumers in the population differ in the the starting
 amount of their asset accounts as well as the trends of their salaries.
 If a consumer has a starting income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{0}$
\end_inset

 and her salary after 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau-\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

 years of working is 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 then at a given age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 (the start of working age is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{0}$
\end_inset

), she could have purchased some long-term durable-goods from a portion
 of her income - deciding that she does not want more durable goods for
 the rest of her life.
 Alternatively, she could have experienced a change in the life-circumstances
 (needing a bigger or a more expensive house) thus needing more durable
 goods urgently.
 The consumption in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 would therefore depend on the needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{\tau}$
\end_inset

, asset account value 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 and the consumption of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{\tau}$
\end_inset

 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 Due to minimal presence of credit facilities in the developing countries,
 we assume an environment of negligible credit.
 This in turn implies that the consumer can only save to buy more of the
 only durable goods available in the market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now consider how two consumers that are vastly separated by their
 respective characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1},\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho_{1}}A<\int_{\rho_{2}}A$
\end_inset

 or vice versa) might behave in the model.
 Recall that the utility through 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 (weight 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\rho})$
\end_inset

 means that someone with a group that has a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 an urbanite or someone in a privileged social class) would be believed
 to be rich - even though her real wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 might be at same level with someone with a lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 a rural person or someone with an underprivileged social class).
 What permits the decomposition of utility through 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into those through 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s(A)-\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 is the social observation of individuals in terms of identities that are
 established through long-term political or economic events.
 Thus an urbanite or someone with a privileged social class might not need
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wealth to indicate a higher status when compared with a rural person or
 someone from an under-privileged class who may have the same or even higher
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wealth.
 Yet since competitions for status matter within one's own social reference
 group and since inference of status is through observation, the individuals
 from respective social classes would continue to compare themselves within
 the same social reference group as well as those outside their social reference
 group - implying the relevance of both 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s(A)-\sigma(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such effects could also mean that the differences in 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 dominate to such an extent that competing with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu,A$
\end_inset

 might not matter towards status competitions.
 Consider what happens when someone changes their social reference group
 (e.g.
 by moving residence or establishing social networks outsides one's reference
 group).
 In such a case, one has to to adjust to the higher (or lower) 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (due to a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(A,\rho)$
\end_inset

).
 However, the very fact that such move is possible (or even subjectively
 imaginable) justifies the existence of a common utility function for all
 consumers.
 There must exist a point of indifference 
\begin_inset Formula $(\rho_{1},A_{1},\nu_{1})\sim(\rho_{2},A_{2},\nu_{2})$
\end_inset

 so that it is feasible that the poorest individual in the privileged social
 class (or the urban area) agrees to trade places with the richest of the
 unprivileged class (or the rural area).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A direct utility approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:loglinearutil"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 could be used to detail a simple intertemporal substitution framework where
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t},\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 are the respective measures for needs, quality and durable goods in the
 time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 If the consumer faced only two periods, then the utilities to be maximised
 in the two periods would be described as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
u_{1}=k_{\psi}log(\psi_{1})+k_{\rho}log(\int_{\rho}A)+k_{\nu,1}log(\nu_{1})+k_{A,1}log(A_{1}-m(\int_{\rho}A))\label{eq:twoperiodoptim}\\
u_{2}=k_{\psi}log(\psi_{2})+k_{\rho}log(\int_{\rho}A)+k_{\nu,2}log(\nu_{2})+k_{A,2}log(A_{2}-m(\int_{\rho}A))\nonumber 
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1},\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 are consumption on quality in periods 1 and 2 respectively while 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1}$
\end_inset

 are value of durable goods at start of the periods 1 and 2.
 The constraints 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\psi}+k_{\rho}+k_{\nu,i}+k_{A,i}=1$
\end_inset

 (for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\ge0$
\end_inset

) apply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In equilibrium, we consider that the utility from 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 are fixed and can thus be assumed to be predetermined for the consumer.
 Thus the consumer choice is not exercised for 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is not far-fetched in a developing economy.
 However, outside the developing economy contexts, if needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 expansion of family) were to be treated as part of the consumer choice,
 we may consider that an individual could delay or suspend the expansion
 of family in order to fulfill a target 
\begin_inset Formula $A-m(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 The basic needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and the utility one gets from 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 for a rich and poor individual may be the same but the costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(A,\rho)$
\end_inset

 the two may face depends both on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 When faced with imminent expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, therefore the consumer could discourage potential changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 so as to maximise 
\begin_inset Formula $A-m(\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

 (by keeping 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A)$
\end_inset

.
 This effect is indeed ignored with the assumption of a predetermined 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 being predetermined for every consumer in the economy implies that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\rho}A$
\end_inset

 is nearly constant with time, the consumer exercises her choice only by
 distributing income between 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nu_{1},A_{1}-m(\int_{\rho_{1}}A))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nu_{2},A_{2}-m(\int_{\rho_{2}}A))$
\end_inset

 in a two-period model.
 In other words, the only true substitution is between 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a typical solution of the intertemporal problem, the wealth constraint
 for the optimisation of 
\begin_inset Formula $U=u_{0}+u_{1}$
\end_inset

 would consider the final 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 all of the consumer's durable goods being liquidated and consumed in the
 last period) and the discounting rate based on 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 - but in our case, we prefer to track the change in asset account 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 at every period i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{t}=A_{t}-A_{t-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Using a dynamic optimisation formulation, we write the following constraints:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
J_{1}\equiv x_{1}-\Psi(\rho,\psi_{1},A_{1})=(P_{\nu,1}\psi_{1})\nu_{1}+\Delta_{1}P_{A,1}\nonumber \\
J_{2}\equiv x_{2}-\Psi(\rho,\psi_{2},A_{2})=(P_{\nu,2}\psi_{2})\nu_{2}+\Delta_{2}P_{A,2}\label{eq:J_constraints}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A,i}$
\end_inset

 is the price of durable-goods in period 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu,i}$
\end_inset

 represents the prices of durable goods and non-durable consumption quality
 respectively.
 The above means that the consumer may consume quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 ( 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{3...}$
\end_inset

 being undefined) in the periods 1 and 2 while she bears the cost of the
 needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi(\rho,\psi_{1},A_{1}),\Psi(\rho,\psi_{2},A_{2})$
\end_inset

 (in periods 1 and 2 respectively).
 She may save for growth to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

 instead of consuming all her outlay 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}=\nu_{t}\psi_{t}+\Psi_{t}(\psi_{t},A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 she can spend all of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}$
\end_inset

 (respectively) or save some of it towards 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we observe the states of the wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

, consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $\{c_{1},c_{2}\},$
\end_inset

 cost of necessities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\Psi_{1},\Psi_{2}\}$
\end_inset

, the prices of quality units (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu,t}$
\end_inset

) and that of durable goods (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A,t}$
\end_inset

), then we can solve for the parameters that govern the utility function
 additive over time i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u=u_{1}+u_{2}$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we assume that the needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 grow deterministically i.e.
 the process 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 is fixed, the outlay to be distributed in expenditure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t},A_{t}$
\end_inset

 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in\{1,2\}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{t}=x_{t}-\Psi(\rho,\psi_{t},A_{t})=\iota(i_{t},\psi_{t},A_{t})$
\end_inset

 (see Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:J_constraints"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 To motivate the dynamic programming approach to this solution, consider
 first what consumer's choices would be in a one-period consumption.
 Here, she could either spend her outlay as 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{_{1}}=\nu_{1}\psi_{1}+\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 or keep the minimum consumption (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=0,c_{1}=\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

) in the period and end up with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}>A_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, then the first-order conditions would provide us the optimal condition
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Let this utility be 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}^{*},A_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 To extend this to two periods with dynamic optimisation one can exploit
 the fact that a consumer independently optimising 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}+u_{2}$
\end_inset

 would always obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}^{*}+u_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This is because if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 are unbounded functions 
\begin_inset Formula $max(u_{1}+u_{2})\le max(u_{1})+max(u_{2})=u_{1}^{*}+u_{2}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 is only a tool to formulate the dynamic optimisation approach - using which
 the value of utility is to be optimised over her life period in a 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

-period model (
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 being the age of the consumer).
 Thus in the optimisation of utility function in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:twoperiodoptim"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the consumer must optimise both 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}$
\end_inset

 in periods 1 and 2 respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have put no restrictions on 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu,1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu,2}$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{A,1},k_{A,2})$
\end_inset

 (other than that they should add to unity in every period).
 Some structure can be added to the consumer choice by introducing life
 life-cycle effects with a form of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu},k_{A}$
\end_inset

 that depends on the age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 of the consumer.
 The rationale is simply that the same level of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 would offer less utility to the consumer as shes age (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 declines with age) or that the same level of long-term durable goods has
 higher utility later in life (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{A}$
\end_inset

 increases with age).
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{\nu},k_{A}$
\end_inset

 could be assumed to have a form 
\begin_inset Formula $n(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\tau)$
\end_inset

 - functions known to the consumer that vary with the age 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 of the consumer.
 In economies that are segregated based on long-term durable goods that
 are largely intergenerational (and thus long-term enough for their utility
 to not change over time), the sensitivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\tau,A)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 may be very little and could allow us to use a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first-order conditions using the Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:twoperiodoptim"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:J_constraints"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 above give us the following Marshallian demand function in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{t},P_{A,t},P_{\nu,t}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
P_{A,t}\Delta_{t}=k_{A,t}(J_{t}-P_{A,t}m(\int_{\rho}A))\\
P_{\nu,t}\psi_{t}\nu_{t}=k_{A,t}(J_{t}-P_{A,t}m(\int_{\rho}A))
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above solution highlights some remarkable features of how a substitution
 between 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 may be influenced by social charactersitics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and life-cycle effects.
 An obvious implication is that higher needs suppress the total outlay for
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Also evident is that in absolute terms, the richer consumers would find
 it more expensive to indicate wealth to their surrounding (it's cheaper
 for a poor person to get richer).
 The equivalent argument applies for quality 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{A,t}$
\end_inset

 increases with time (due to the form that we've assumed), the consumer
 would increase her ownership of durable goods accordingly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While the above model does explain a substitution between 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t},A_{t}$
\end_inset

 with stated assumptions, there are reasons to doubt both the utility of
 a loglinear formulation for empirical analyses and validity of the forms
 
\begin_inset Formula $n(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 As we show with the help of a cost-function formulation, the loglinear
 utility does limit how status utility could relate to price of quality
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A}$
\end_inset

 - the variation of which with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 provides a particular context to status consumption.
 Thus while we have used the direct utility model to explain the model dynamics,
 a cost-function formulation provides a more general framework for the econometr
ic analyses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first look at the limitation posed by the log-linear utility in more
 detail.
 For a general 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\beta_{i}log(q_{i}-\gamma_{i})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum{\beta_{i}}=1$
\end_inset

, if the budget constraint is set to be 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{i}p_{i}q_{i}=\textbf{p}\cdot\textbf{q}$
\end_inset

, then the optimisation using a Lagrangian leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $L=u-\lambda(\sum{p_{i}q_{i}}-x)$
\end_inset

.
 The first-order conditions imply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
x=\sum{p_{i}q_{i}}\\
\frac{\beta_{i}}{q_{i}-\gamma_{i}}=\lambda p_{i}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum{\beta_{i}}=1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda(x-\sum{p_{i}\gamma_{i}})=1$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(q_{i}-\gamma_{i})=\beta_{i}(x-\sum{p_{i}\gamma_{i}})$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 the Marshallian demand function).
 The indirect utility function - of which cost function is the inverse of
 - can be written as 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The example in the discussion is provided in Deaton
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonEconConsumer"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - which is also excellent resource on the duality theory and cost-functions.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
u & =\sum{\beta_{i}}log(q_{i}-\gamma_{i})=\sum\beta_{i}log(\frac{\beta_{i}}{p_{i}}(x-\sum{p_{k}\gamma_{k}}))
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once again, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum{\beta_{k}}=1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\sum\beta_{i}log(\frac{\beta_{i}}{p_{i}})+\sum\beta_{i}log((x-\sum{p_{k}\gamma_{k}}))\Rightarrow u=\sum\beta_{i}log(\frac{\beta_{i}}{p_{i}})+log(x-\sum{p_{k}\gamma_{k}})$
\end_inset

.
 The cost function thus becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
log(c(u,\textbf{p})-\sum{p_{k}\gamma_{k}}) & =u-\sum\beta_{i}log(\frac{\beta_{i}}{p_{i}})\label{eq:loglineargeneral}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The PIGLOG (Price Invariant Generalized Logarithmic) cost-functions - which
 are based on the assumption that the utility scales up linearly with the
 logarithm of outlay i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\frac{log(x)-a(p)}{b(p)-a(p)}$
\end_inset

, would be of the form 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
log(c(u,\textbf{p}) & =a(p)(1-u)+b(p)u\label{eq:PIGLOG}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An useful intuition for the PIGLOG cost-functions (see Deaton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonMuellbauerAIDS"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) is its view as a linear decomposition of the logarithm of outlay (
\begin_inset Formula $log(x)$
\end_inset

) into costs of subsistence (
\begin_inset Formula $u=0$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a(p)$
\end_inset

) and bliss (
\begin_inset Formula $u=1$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b(p)$
\end_inset

).
 In this form, the cost function in the Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:loglineargeneral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 would be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
log(c(u,\textbf{p})-\sum{p_{k}\gamma_{k}}) & =(1-\sum\beta_{i}log(\frac{\beta_{i}}{p_{i}}))u+(-\sum\beta_{i}log(\frac{\beta_{i}}{p_{i}}))(1-u)
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost-function formulation shows just how restrictive a loglinear direct
 utility function really is.
 The above direct utility form of the loglinear utility claims that the
 price derivatives of cost-functions (which are typically equated with the
