\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 is same for both 
\begin_inset Formula $R'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, the overall quality does not simply add up over multiple commodity groups
 (over energy or durable goods for example).
 In fact, there is little sense in claiming that the quality in one commodity
 can be substituted with quality in another.
 The idea of overall quality is meaningful only with the consideration of
 a total cost of basic needs level 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The notion of excess - subject to such a level - is thus the only a way
 to assess overall quality in non-durable consumption.
 Thus if having a refrigerator is not considered a need, then we may say
 nothing more than that 
\begin_inset Formula $R'$
\end_inset

 spends more on food quality than 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has more durable goods than 
\begin_inset Formula $R'$
\end_inset

.
 By avoiding counting maintenance costs in 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, we merely maintain the same interpretation
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is possible that ownership of some durable goods generates some rental
 income.
 Although we haven't found the significance of such income in the consumption
 data, such income would be considered an additional stream of income instead
 of reduction in the cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The empirical method for adjusting necessities based on the durable goods
 one possesses is straightforward if we assume a typical usage for all expensive
 durable goods owned.
 If a household possesses a car, then the needs of the household would be
 incremented with the petrol consumption per year and maintenance for a
 typical usage.
 This also means that some costs of needs (e.g.
 for food) are multiplied by the number of household members in the family
 while other needs aren't - as we obtain the cost of needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 for a particular household (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Needs-Cost"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The classification of long-term durable goods is based on intergenerational
 transfers i.e.
 an item is included in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (and thus its cost of maintenance are included in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

) only if it can be passed on through generations.
 The durable goods that cannot be passed through generations are not considered
 long-term and excluded from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (this is due to the life-cycle considerations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since social characteristics are acquired over a life-time and often require
 some investment (e.g.
 education fees or club-membership fees), one could - from a rather theoretical
 standpoint - treat such social characteristics too as durable-good.
 Although we do treat education as a personal characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 in our analyses, the case could be made for education to be treated as
 a long-term durable good as well (which is valid for an inter-generational
 transfer, requires a long investment over time and has a certain value
 in the employment market).
 While such a consideration is not prevented in the model for consumer choice,
 we do impose the condition that for a long-term choice (such as committing
 to the education of one's progeny) to be considered part of the durable
 goods 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the costs of maintenance (e.g.
 school fees) associated with the durable-goods should be included in the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 If not, then such a long-term choice - improves one's relative positioning
 directly and must be considered as part of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 (moving residence or entering a new social network are such examples).
 In other words, education could be treated as a durable good in the regular
 sense only as long as an educated individual is required to pay definite
 maintenance costs for having been educated.
\end_layout

